444
00:31:56,620 --> 00:32:00,230
I don't want this bit. I'm calling the police.

445
00:32:00,230 --> 00:32:02,610
Four days ago, I watched him sleep with a woman called Vicky...

446
00:32:02,610 --> 00:32:04,130
Mark. Mark, please! And it broke my heart.

447
00:32:04,130 --> 00:32:06,430
Four days ago, she - Sarah's ghost - saw you

448
00:32:06,430 --> 00:32:08,620
sleeping with a woman called Vicky...

449
00:32:09,540 --> 00:32:11,120
and it broke her heart.

450
00:32:12,120 --> 00:32:13,810
There's no way I could know that.

451
00:32:17,520 --> 00:32:19,090
Fuck off.

452
00:32:25,300 --> 00:32:28,930
We were Angelics.
I still am one.

453
00:32:30,730 --> 00:32:32,630
We're a different breed of people.

454
00:32:32,990 --> 00:32:35,100
We were sworn to secrecy, Mark.

455
00:32:37,410 --> 00:32:38,760
You two were my best friends,

456
00:32:38,760 --> 00:32:42,530
so I'm here tonight to try to make it right for yous.

457
00:32:45,300 --> 00:32:46,950
I don't understand...

458
00:32:48,400 --> 00:32:49,760
She's dead?

459
00:32:50,350 --> 00:32:53,800
Yeah. She's here now, Mark.

460
00:32:54,690 --> 00:32:56,200
She doesn't want to leave you.

461
00:32:57,080 --> 00:32:58,050
She's...

462
00:32:58,770 --> 00:33:02,440
Let's all keep calm, and we'll ask her some questions, yeah?

463
00:33:02,440 --> 00:33:05,730
She's... she's...

464
00:33:10,140 --> 00:33:13,980
Am I looking at her? Yeah. Just about. She's...

465
00:33:16,850 --> 00:33:19,350
I'm going to repeat what Sarah says word for word.

466
00:33:20,260 --> 00:33:22,080
What do you want to ask her, Mark?

467
00:33:31,850 --> 00:33:34,200
PAUL:WAKE UP!

468
00:33:55,500 --> 00:33:58,520
I want to tell you about something wonderful.

469
00:33:59,110 --> 00:34:02,770
I want to tell you about Gaia. What's Gaia?

470
00:34:03,630 --> 00:34:05,800
Call yourself a geek? "What's Gaia?"

471
00:34:05,800 --> 00:34:07,550
You're a disgrace to your community.

472
00:34:08,440 --> 00:34:10,580
Did Neil Gaiman write it?

473
00:34:11,030 --> 00:34:14,440
Look, do you want me to help fix it with Jay, or what?

474
00:34:14,910 --> 00:34:18,200
Hmm? Right. In 2012,

475
00:34:18,200 --> 00:34:22,130
we're sending the satellite Gaia into the galaxy

476
00:34:22,130 --> 00:34:24,840
to take pictures of the stars.

477
00:34:33,340 --> 00:34:35,030
What's this? Cough medicine.

478
00:34:35,030 --> 00:34:40,330
Its billion-pixel camera will give scientists a 3D map of the sky.

479
00:34:40,330 --> 00:34:42,570
Cough medicine? Takes the edge off.

480
00:34:42,570 --> 00:34:47,700
It'll tell us about the Milky Way, how it works, how it started,

481
00:34:47,700 --> 00:34:52,750
but the exciting thing is the things we're not expecting to see.

482
00:34:52,750 --> 00:34:56,740
Asteroids, planets beyond our solar system,

483
00:34:56,740 --> 00:34:59,760
tepid stars that never fired into life.

484
00:34:59,760 --> 00:35:04,110
Extraordinary things we don't understand.

485
00:35:11,560 --> 00:35:13,010
Now call her.

486
00:35:13,720 --> 00:35:15,190
But I can't.

487
00:35:16,030 --> 00:35:18,190
Yeah, you can.
Mac...

488
00:35:20,870 --> 00:35:22,780
It's ringing. Mac.

489
00:35:31,910 --> 00:35:34,520
I am not a morning person.

490
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:36,540
'Look out the window.'

491
00:35:44,610 --> 00:35:48,610
'The point is... 'Gaia is extraordinary.

492
00:35:48,610 --> 00:35:52,050
'It's going to show us amazing things we can't even contemplate.

493
00:35:52,470 --> 00:35:55,540
'It's also really, really ordinary.'

494
00:35:55,540 --> 00:35:58,270
Wow. That's a look.

495
00:35:58,270 --> 00:36:00,010
Because you know what's best about Gaia?

496
00:36:00,010 --> 00:36:03,400
Because... because do you want to know the best thing about Gaia?

497
00:36:03,400 --> 00:36:05,250
Chelmsford and Stevenage.

498
00:36:05,250 --> 00:36:08,910
Where it was made. Chelmsford and Stevenage.

499
00:36:08,910 --> 00:36:12,170
A bunch of geeky men, sitting in a shit town

500
00:36:12,170 --> 00:36:15,850
built something that would transform the way we look at the skies.

501
00:36:15,850 --> 00:36:19,820
The things that scare you about me...

502
00:36:19,820 --> 00:36:21,070
Imagine...

503
00:36:22,510 --> 00:36:24,660
Imagine I'm Stevenage.

504
00:36:24,970 --> 00:36:30,740
Some things have changed about me, but fundamentally I'm... I'm just ordinary.

505
00:36:32,460 --> 00:36:34,550
I'm... Stevenage.

506
00:36:35,890 --> 00:36:37,280
Smooth as.

507
00:36:37,880 --> 00:36:40,830
So, you're Superman, right?

508
00:36:42,420 --> 00:36:46,140
I can't hear you. Yes, you can. I can hear you.

509
00:36:46,360 --> 00:36:50,210
Well, you must have supersonic hearing, then. I can't hear a word.

510
00:36:50,210 --> 00:36:55,220
You're quite the loser, you know that? Hang on a minute.

511
00:37:03,120 --> 00:37:06,270
I think this is the time when I do the alpha thing and say

512
00:37:06,270 --> 00:37:10,010
you look great as you are. No "quite" about it - you're a loser!

513
00:37:10,010 --> 00:37:12,430
Yeah. A loser. I know.

514
00:37:13,530 --> 00:37:15,500
Now everyone knows about us.

